'''Ozeki Shrine''' (おぜきじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Asai-chō|Q11556970|WD=Q11556970|lt=Asai-chō|1=Azai}}, {{ill|lt=Ichinomiya|Q270810|WD=Q270810|1=Ichinomiya, Aichi}}, {{ill|lt=Aichi Prefecture|Q80434|WD=Q80434|1=Aichi Prefecture}}. Its former {{ill|lt=shrine rank|Q10444029|WD=Q10444029|1=Shakaku}} was gōsha. It is the origin of the local place name “Ozeki.”

It is presumed to be “Ozeki Shrine” of {{ill|lt=Nakajima District|Q780420|WD=Q780420|1=Nakashima district}}, {{ill|lt=Owari Province|Q514506|WD=Q514506|1=Owari Province}}, in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|lt=Engishiki|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}. However, this area is in {{ill|lt=Haguri District|Q1032507|WD=Q1032507|1=Haguri District}} of Owari, so this is questioned. Still, there are similar cases: “Ishitō Shrine,” also a Shikinaisha of Nakajima District, is theorized to be {{ill|lt=Ishitō Shrine (Asai-chō, Ichinomiya)|Q11585184|WD=Q11585184|1=Iwato Shrine}}, and {{ill|lt=Asai Shrine (Ichinomiya)|Q11556984|WD=Q11556984|1=Azai Shrine (Ichinomiya)}}, also a Nakajima District Shikinaisha, exists in Haguri District. Since this region frequently flooded by the {{ill|lt=Kiso River|Q779607|WD=Q779607|1=Kiso River}}, another theory says district boundaries in the Heian period were unclear, so this area may also have belonged to Nakajima District.

=== Overview ===
*Foundation period is unknown. The main sanctuary stands on a {{ill|lt=keyhole-shaped kofun|Q11268718|WD=Q11268718|1=Zenpō-kōen-fun}}. This kofun is traditionally said to be the tomb of Ozeki Sukune Yumihari (ancestor of the {{ill|lt=Owari clan|Q11465311|WD=Q11465311|1=Owari clan}}). The area is a dense zone of small kofun known as the Asai Kofun Group. {{ill|lt=Asai Shrine (Ichinomiya)|Q11556984|WD=Q11556984|lt=Asai Shrine|1=Azai Shrine (Ichinomiya)}} also has its shrine buildings on a kofun.
*In the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963|1=Edo period}}, it was called Funatsuki Daimyōjin. There was a landing here, and boats for Ise Shrine pilgrimages are said to have come and gone using the Kiso River.
*In {{ill|lt=1873|Q7757|WD=Q7757|1=1873}} (Meiji 6), it was renamed back to Ozeki Shrine and became a village shrine.
*In {{ill|lt=1909|Q2057|WD=Q2057|1=1909}} (Meiji 42), Saigūshi Shrine, Nishi-Shinmei-sha, and Atago-sha were merged.
*In {{ill|lt=1936|Q18649|WD=Q18649|1=1936}} (Shōwa 11), it became gōsha.

=== Enshrined deities ===
;Main deity
:*{{ill|lt=Ame-no-Hoakari-no-Mikoto|Q10940411|WD=Q10940411|1=Amenohoakari}}
;Merged deities
:*Kagutsuchi-no-Mikoto
:*Ame-kaguyama-no-Mikoto
:*{{ill|lt=Amaterasu|Q455602|WD=Q455602|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami|1=Amaterasu}}

=== Cultural properties ===
* Ozeki Shrine Kofun - Aichi Prefecture designated historic site, one of the Asai Kofun Group
* Shrine forest - Ichinomiya City designated natural monument

=== Transportation ===
*Get off at {{ill|lt=Meitetsu Bus|Q6810397|WD=Q6810397|1=Meitetsu Bus}} “Ozeki” stop, 5 minutes on foot
**From {{ill|lt=Meitetsu Ichinomiya Station|Q2856589|WD=Q2856589|1=Meitetsu Ichinomiya Station}} on the {{ill|lt=Nagoya Main Line|Q1137838|WD=Q1137838|1=Meitetsu Nagoya Main Line}}/{{ill|lt=Bisai Line|Q901005|WD=Q901005|1=Meitetsu Bisai Line}} of {{ill|lt=Nagoya Railroad|Q30850|WD=Q30850|1=Meitetsu}}, or {{ill|lt=Owari-Ichinomiya Station|Q871495|WD=Q871495|1=Owari-Ichinomiya Station}} on the {{ill|lt=Tōkaidō Main Line|Q1190152|WD=Q1190152|1=Tōkaidō Main Line}} (Meitetsu Ichinomiya Station bus terminal platform 3), take bus bound for “Miyata Hongō”

